    <p>Lion's mane (Hericium erinaceus) is a medicinal mushroom clinically shown to stimulate nerve growth factor (NGF) production in the brain. This unique mechanism supports memory, focus, cognitive function, and nerve repair. A 2009 study in <em>Phytotherapy Research</em> found that adults taking 3g of lion's mane daily for 16 weeks showed significant improvements in cognitive function compared to placebo. Unlike caffeine or synthetic nootropics, lion's mane works by supporting the brain's own growth and repair mechanisms — a fundamentally different approach to cognitive enhancement.</p>

    <p>This guide covers everything the clinical literature tells us about lion's mane: what it does, how it works at the molecular level, all 8 science-backed benefits, optimal dosage by supplement form, the critical difference between fruiting body and mycelium products, side effects, and how it compares to other popular nootropics. If you are considering lion's mane supplementation for brain health, this is the most comprehensive evidence-based resource available. For product recommendations, see our guide to the <a href="/mushroom/lions-mane-gummies/">best lion's mane gummies</a>.</p>

