    <!-- SECTION 1: WHAT IS LION'S MANE? -->
    <h2>What Is Lion's Mane Mushroom?</h2>

    <p>Lion's mane (Hericium erinaceus) is a large, white, shaggy mushroom that grows on hardwood trees throughout North America, Europe, and Asia. Its distinctive cascading spines resemble a lion's mane — hence the name. In Traditional Chinese Medicine, lion's mane has been used for centuries to support digestive health and overall vitality. In Japan, it is known as yamabushitake and has a long culinary and medicinal history. But the modern scientific interest in lion's mane began in the 1990s when Japanese researchers discovered something remarkable: this mushroom produces compounds that stimulate the brain to make its own nerve growth factor.</p>

    <p>Unlike most medicinal mushrooms that are valued primarily for immune-modulating beta-glucans, lion's mane contains two classes of compounds found in no other mushroom — hericenones and erinacines. These compounds are responsible for lion's mane's unique neurotrophic (nerve-growing) effects, and they are what separate lion's mane from every other functional mushroom on the market.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Hericenones</h4>
        <p>Found exclusively in the <strong>fruiting body</strong> (the visible mushroom). Hericenones stimulate NGF production in astrocytes — brain cells that support and nourish neurons. These compounds are responsible for the cognitive benefits associated with lion's mane extract.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="activity" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Erinacines</h4>
        <p>Found primarily in the <strong>mycelium</strong> (root-like network). Erinacines are small enough to cross the blood-brain barrier and directly stimulate NGF synthesis within the central nervous system. They are among the most potent natural NGF inducers ever discovered.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Beta-Glucans</h4>
        <p>Like other medicinal mushrooms, lion's mane contains beta-glucans — polysaccharides that modulate immune function. These compounds activate macrophages, natural killer cells, and dendritic cells, providing immune support alongside the neurological benefits.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Centuries of Use</h4>
        <p>Lion's mane has been used in Traditional Chinese Medicine for over 1,000 years, traditionally prescribed for digestive ailments and general vitality. Modern science has validated and expanded on these traditional uses with rigorous clinical trials.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The key distinction to understand is that lion's mane is not a stimulant. It does not increase alertness by blocking adenosine receptors (like caffeine) or flooding the brain with dopamine (like Adderall). Instead, it supports the brain's own infrastructure — promoting the growth of new neurons, strengthening existing neural connections, and protecting against age-related degeneration. This makes lion's mane fundamentally different from every other cognitive enhancer, and it is why the effects build gradually over weeks of consistent use rather than appearing immediately.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 2: HOW LION'S MANE WORKS -->
    <h2>How Lion's Mane Works: NGF and Brain Health</h2>

    <p>To understand what lion's mane does, you need to understand nerve growth factor (NGF). NGF is a protein that was discovered by Nobel Prize-winning neuroscientist Rita Levi-Montalcini in the 1950s. It is essential for the survival, development, and function of neurons — particularly in the hippocampus (the brain region responsible for memory) and the peripheral nervous system. When NGF levels decline — as they naturally do with aging — neurons become more vulnerable to damage, synaptic connections weaken, and cognitive function deteriorates.</p>

    <p>Lion's mane is the only known food source that stimulates the brain to produce more NGF. The hericenones in the fruiting body and the erinacines in the mycelium both activate this pathway, though through slightly different mechanisms. A landmark 2008 study by Mori et al. in <em>Biological and Pharmaceutical Bulletin</em> demonstrated that lion's mane extract significantly increased NGF levels in cultured astrocytes — the brain cells responsible for producing and releasing NGF.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">230%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">increase in NGF synthesis was observed in vitro when astrocytes were exposed to lion's mane extract containing hericenones. <strong>Source: Mori et al., 2008, Biological and Pharmaceutical Bulletin.</strong> This is one of the largest NGF increases documented from any natural compound, and it explains why lion's mane has such broad neurological effects.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>The NGF Pathway — Step by Step</h3>

    <p>Here is exactly how lion's mane supports brain health at the molecular level:</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="star" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Step 1: Bioactive Compounds Reach the Brain</h4>
        <p>After ingestion, hericenones and erinacines are absorbed through the gut and enter the bloodstream. Erinacines are small enough to cross the blood-brain barrier directly. Hericenones stimulate NGF production from the peripheral side.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Step 2: NGF Synthesis Increases</h4>
        <p>These compounds activate astrocytes — brain support cells — to produce and release more NGF. Higher NGF levels mean neurons receive stronger growth and survival signals.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="activity" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Step 3: Myelin Sheath Repair</h4>
        <p>NGF stimulates myelination — the process of coating nerve fibers with an insulating myelin sheath. Intact myelin is essential for fast, accurate signal transmission between neurons. Damaged myelin leads to cognitive slowing and neurological disorders.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="award" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Step 4: Enhanced Neuroplasticity</h4>
        <p>With increased NGF, the brain forms new synaptic connections more efficiently — a process called neuroplasticity. This is the biological basis of learning, memory formation, and cognitive adaptation. More neuroplasticity means a more resilient, adaptable brain.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>This NGF-mediated mechanism is what makes lion's mane unique among nootropics. While most cognitive enhancers temporarily alter neurotransmitter levels (providing short-term effects that disappear when you stop taking them), lion's mane promotes structural changes in the brain — new neural connections, repaired myelin, and more robust neuron survival. These are changes that persist and compound over time, which is why consistent long-term supplementation produces the most significant results.</p>

