    <!-- SECTION 6: FRUITING BODY VS MYCELIUM -->
    <h2>Fruiting Body vs Mycelium: The Critical Quality Difference</h2>

    <p>This is the most important quality distinction in lion's mane supplementation — and the one most supplement companies hope you do not understand. The mushroom you see growing on a tree is the fruiting body. The root-like network that grows inside the substrate (usually grain) is the mycelium. They contain different bioactive compounds, and the difference in potency is enormous.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="award" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Fruiting Body (Superior)</h4>
        <p><strong>Contains hericenones — the primary NGF stimulators.</strong> Higher beta-glucan content (typically 20-40%). No grain filler. The fruiting body is the part used in the clinical trials that demonstrated cognitive benefits. Products labeled "fruiting body extract" or "100% fruiting body" use this superior source material. This is what you want.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-circle" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Mycelium on Grain (Inferior for Most Uses)</h4>
        <p><strong>Contains erinacines but often heavily diluted with grain starch.</strong> Many mycelium products are grown on brown rice and the final product is ground mycelium + grain together — sometimes 50-70% grain starch with minimal beta-glucans. These products test low for bioactive compounds and cost less to produce. The label often says "mycelium biomass" or "full-spectrum mycelium."</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">⚠️</span>
      <p><strong>How to identify low-quality products:</strong> If the supplement facts panel lists "myceliated grain" or "mycelium biomass" as the source — and the starch content is high while beta-glucan content is low or unstated — you are paying for a product that is mostly rice flour with trace amounts of lion's mane. Always look for products that specify "fruiting body" and list a beta-glucan percentage (ideally 20%+). The clinical trials demonstrating cognitive benefits used fruiting body extract, not mycelium on grain.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The ideal lion's mane supplement uses either 100% fruiting body extract (for hericenones and beta-glucans) or a dual-extract combining fruiting body and purified mycelium extract (for both hericenones and erinacines). Avoid products that list "mycelium" as the sole source without specifying that the mycelium has been extracted and separated from the grain substrate. For our lab-tested product recommendations, see our full <a href="/mushroom/lions-mane-gummies/">lion's mane gummies</a> guide.</p>

