    <!-- SECTION 9: SIDE EFFECTS -->
    <h2>Side Effects and Safety</h2>

    <p>Lion's mane has an excellent safety profile in human clinical trials. It has been consumed as food in East Asia for centuries and has been studied in controlled trials at doses up to 3g daily for 16 weeks without serious adverse effects. That said, a small percentage of users may experience mild side effects, and certain populations should exercise caution.</p>

    <h3>Common Side Effects (Mild, Infrequent)</h3>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-circle" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Itchy Skin</h4>
        <p>The most commonly reported side effect — likely related to increased NGF activity, as NGF is involved in skin nerve sensitivity. This is usually mild, transient, and resolves with continued use or dose reduction. It may actually indicate the supplement is bioactive.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="activity" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>GI Discomfort</h4>
        <p>Some users report mild stomach discomfort, bloating, or nausea — particularly at higher doses or when starting supplementation. Taking lion's mane with food typically resolves this. Starting at a lower dose and increasing gradually also helps.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">⚠️</span>
      <p><strong>Mushroom allergy warning:</strong> People with known allergies to mushrooms should NOT take lion's mane supplements. Cross-reactivity between mushroom species is common. If you experience hives, swelling, difficulty breathing, or anaphylactic symptoms after taking lion's mane, discontinue immediately and seek medical attention. People on anticoagulant medications (warfarin, heparin) should consult their physician before supplementing, as lion's mane may have mild antiplatelet properties.</p>
    </div>

    <p>For the vast majority of healthy adults, lion's mane at 500-3000mg daily is safe, well-tolerated, and carries no risk of dependency, tolerance, or withdrawal. Unlike caffeine and prescription stimulants, lion's mane does not produce jitteriness, anxiety, or sleep disruption. It can be stopped at any time without rebound cognitive decline — though the NGF-mediated benefits will gradually diminish over weeks to months after discontinuation.</p>

