      <details class="fq"><summary>What does lion's mane mushroom do for the brain?</summary><p>Lion's mane stimulates the production of nerve growth factor (NGF) through two unique compounds — hericenones and erinacines — that cross the blood-brain barrier. NGF is essential for neuron growth, survival, and repair. A 2009 study in <em>Phytotherapy Research</em> found that 3g of lion's mane daily for 16 weeks significantly improved cognitive function in adults with mild cognitive impairment. The mechanism supports memory formation, focus, neuroplasticity, and may slow age-related cognitive decline.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take for lion's mane to work?</summary><p>Most clinical studies show measurable cognitive benefits at 4-16 weeks of consistent daily use. Some users report improvements in focus and mental clarity within 2-3 weeks. The 2009 trial demonstrated significant improvements at 16 weeks. NGF production and nerve regeneration are gradual biological processes — lion's mane is not an acute stimulant. Consistent daily dosing for at least 8 weeks is recommended before evaluating effectiveness.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best dosage for lion's mane?</summary><p>The effective range is 500-3000mg daily. For standardized extract (10:1 or higher concentration), 500-1000mg is sufficient. For raw mushroom powder, 1500-3000mg is needed. Gummies typically provide 500-1000mg per serving. Clinical trials used 750-3000mg daily. Start with 500mg and increase gradually. No serious side effects have been reported at doses up to 3g per day for 16 weeks.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is lion's mane safe to take every day?</summary><p>Yes. Clinical trials lasting up to 16 weeks at 3g daily reported no serious adverse effects. The most common side effects are mild GI discomfort and, rarely, itchy skin. People with mushroom allergies should avoid lion's mane. Those on anticoagulant medications should consult a physician. No dependency, tolerance, or withdrawal effects have been documented.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does lion's mane actually improve memory?</summary><p>Yes, with clinical evidence. The 2009 double-blind trial found significant improvements in cognitive function scores in adults with mild cognitive impairment after 16 weeks. A 2020 study confirmed improvements in short-term and recognition memory in healthy adults after 12 weeks. The mechanism is NGF-mediated enhancement of hippocampal function — the brain region responsible for memory consolidation.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take lion's mane in the morning or at night?</summary><p>Most practitioners recommend morning or early afternoon because its primary effects — focus, mental clarity, and cognitive performance — are most useful during waking hours. Lion's mane is not sedating. If taking divided doses, take one in the morning and one at lunch. If combined with a mushroom stack, take lion's mane in the morning and reishi at night for the AM/PM protocol.</p></details>
